    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-01-03T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-01-03T02:00:00-05:00" n="636"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d636">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.116/121: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China (<persName type="from"
                            >Johnson</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-01-03T15:00:00+08:00"
                            >January 3, 1934—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 3—8 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5. Department’s 374, November 13, 6 p.m.<note n="4" xml:id="d636fn4">Not
                        printed.</note> Following from Consul General, Canton, to the Legation and
                    Nanking: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“December 29, 11 a.m. Present status of kerosene question is as follows:
                            Registration of foreign oil companies effected December 19. Liquid fuel
                            for refining is being imported without restrictions. Although companies
                            have not yet begun to market oil refined from these imports, they do not
                            anticipate that sales will be restricted if they pay the prescribed tax.
                            The tax regulations, as published in the press, however, provide for a
                            system whereby the tax, amounting to $3 national currency per 10
                            gallons, can be paid for with debentures purchased for one-third cash
                            down. The foreign companies are apprehensive that this means that the
                            native companies will be relieved of the necessity of paying the
                            balance, thus resulting in a discrimination in their favor to the extent
                            of $2 per 10 gallons. The foreign companies are now planning to
                            institute test cases to determine how the regulations will be enforced
                            in practice.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
